> int:\n        def is_square(n):\n            return int(n**0.5) ** 2 == n\n        \n        def backtrack(path):\n            if len(path) == len(nums):\n                self.count += 1\n                return\n            \n            for num in count:\n                if count[num] > 0:\n                    if not path or is_square(path[-1] + num):\n                        count[num] -= 1\n                        backtrack(path + [num])\n                        count[num] += 1\n        \n        self.count = 0\n        count = Counter(nums)\n        backtrack([])\n        return self.count\n```\n\nThis solution uses backtracking to explore all possible permutations of the given array `nums` and checks if the sum of every pair of adjacent elements is a perfect square. The `Counter` from the `collections` module is used to handle duplicate elements efficiently. The `is_square` helper function checks if a number is a perfect square. The `backtrack` function recursively builds permutations and counts the valid ones.", "estimated_date": 1550361600000}